  "prompt": "What are the main reasons why students from Princeton don't graduate on time?",
  "response": "While I don't have access to specific data or internal reports from Princeton University as of 2023, students at any prestigious institution may face certain common challenges that could affect their ability to graduate on time. Here are some potential reasons:\n\n1. **Academic Difficulty:** Rigorous academic standards and challenging coursework can sometimes lead to delays. Students might need to retake classes or might struggle to maintain the GPA required for their major.\n\n2. **Changing Majors:** Switching majors or fields of study can result in needing additional time to complete the new set of required courses.\n\n3. **Personal Health Issues:** Physical or mental health challenges can cause students to take time off or reduce their course load.\n\n4. **Financial Constraints:** Financial difficulties may necessitate part-time work or a leave of absence, thereby extending the time required to graduate.\n\n5. **Extracurricular Commitments:** Heavy involvement in extracurricular activities, internships, or research projects might detract from the focus on completing coursework in a timely manner.\n\n6. **Study Abroad Programs:** Participation in semester-long or year-long study abroad programs can sometimes add to the duration of study if courses taken abroad do not fully align with degree requirements.\n\n7. **Family Obligations:** Personal or family responsibilities may require students to take leaves of absence or reduce their course load.\n\n8. **Advising and Planning:** Ineffective academic advising or lack of proper planning can lead to students missing required courses or taking unnecessary electives, thereby extending their academic timeline.\n\n9. **Administrative Issues:** Problems related to course availability, scheduling conflicts, or bureaucratic hurdles can also contribute to delays in graduation.\n\nFor precise information, it would be best to consult Princeton's academic advising resources or statistical reports from the university itself.",
